{
  "answer": "**Manusmṛti (also known as the *Laws of Manu*), Chapter 8.**\n\nThis text prescribes graduated penalties for theft (the \"guilt\" here referring to the fine or restitution owed, scaled by caste or *varṇa*) as follows: eightfold for a Shudra (the lowest order), sixteenfold for a Vaishya (the next), thirty-twofold for a Kshatriya (warrior), and sixty-fourfold (or up to a hundred or twice sixty-four) for a Brahmana (priestly class). The explicit reason given for the Brahmana facing the highest penalty is that \"he is a knower of the good and bad qualities of that act.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: Manusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-fc6559).  \n\"For a theft, the guilt of a Shudra shall be eightfold; of a Vaishya, sixteenfold; of a Kshatriya, thirty-twofold. // Mn_8.337 //\"  \nManusmṛti, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/08/translation/#p-30e5e8).  \n\"For a Brahmana, it shall be sixty-fourfold, or a full hundred, or even twice sixty-four; for he is a knower of the good and bad qualities of that act. // Mn_8.338 //\"",
